Prologue
"Please!" Queen Alvin pleaded, "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with royal advisors standing by his side. The queen had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, the Ice King couldn't help but furrow his brow.
The infant girl looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, with a few strands of blue hair scattered through it. The Ice King believed that having a daughter would make him seem weak. After all, before this, he had only ever had sons.
"You have only two choices: either kill the child or leave her out in the wilderness. This is your punishment, Alvin," he said, uttering her name with venom, as if it were poison. He always did this.
The Land of Frost was not always a single kingdom. It once split into two parts, the north and the south. The north established a non-magical kingdom, while the south became a kingdom brimming with magical power. Due to the north's greed, the two kingdoms waged endless wars until the south proposed a truce.
At that time, the South had already fallen into despair, and the royal family was willing to do anything to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed marrying their only princess to the North, making her the Northern queen and having a son who would become the future king. Afterward, the South would merge with the North to establish a unified kingdom. The North accepted this proposal, and thus Princess Elvin married Prince Acurl.
"Please, my king, for the safety of my child, you can do anything to me—imprison me, exile me, even kill me," Queen Elvin pleaded, cradling her child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at the Queen, his eyes filled with contempt. Perhaps, just perhaps, he felt a flicker of pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him during his darkest moments, and had given him children.
"Alright. The child can live in the palace." The queen sighed in relief upon hearing the Ice King's words. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Alvin both showed expressions of alarm. She slowly lowered her head and looked at the floor. "As you command, my king," she bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to take the Queen's daughter to one of Alvin's empty rooms. After that, he commanded the guards to bring Alvin to the public square where all the citizens could see, to be executed.
When the guards led her to the execution ground, the citizens, seeing their only queen—and the kindest queen—on the verge of being executed, felt extremely angry. Some cried, others shouted and tried to attack the guards, while some wondered why such a thing had happened; yet they all shared the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why did they treat her like that?"
As Arvin approached the wooden post, the most terrifying person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner who carried out burnings. Queen Alwen would be burned alive. No one should be subjected to burning, not even criminals. In the Frostlands, burning was the cruelest punishment.
Arvin was tied to a wooden post, and the king began to recount how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Frost Kingdom refused to believe and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner set fire to the wooden post, and a single tear rolled down the former queen's face.
"Carly, hang on!" The life of Queen Alvin came to an end.
The hall was silent.
In the south wing of this icy palace, an endless "tap-tap" sound came from the room farthest to the left. The passing servants were always curious about what was inside but were too frightened to approach. The maids moved about the hall, whispering among themselves and spreading all sorts of rumors. Some believed that the late queen, Elvin, the wife of the Ice King, was confined in that room, waiting to be set free.
They were very wrong. As Avery thought, he walked toward the south wing, where the servants moved back and forth along the walls, whispering among themselves. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there are also many rumors about TA, because TA is the only person allowed to enter the room.
Knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you inside?" Avery whispered to the intricate door adorned with snowflakes and a crown, symbols of royalty.
TA didn't know if she would really let him in this time—it was different from before. There were still bruises from last time on my body. Avery recalled the incident and couldn't help but laugh. At that time, Carly had thrown a book at him, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A soft sound came from the room, as if saying she couldn't go anywhere but stay right there.
"Avery asked, 'May I come in?' remembering all too well the consequences of last time when they had entered without being asked."
A faint sound came again from the room, as if saying, "Come in." Avery felt a chill, unsure whether it was from the cold or the sound. Although TA had been there for many years, Avery still found it a bit strange to hear a voice coming from the room.
"I'm coming in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. By normal standards, the scene inside the room was unusual, but it wasn't unexpected. Paper was everywhere. Books were scattered on the floor, the table was broken, and there were many ice sculptures around the room. There were no windows, and there was almost no light. It was also colder than the rest of the palace (which raised many questions). The room looked as if it had been hit by a blizzard—everything was in chaos.
The girl in the room was curled up on the bed, wrapped in blankets, reading from a notebook. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Avery sat by Carly's bed and asked, 'Which notebook are you reading?'"
